"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Matthew chapters 21–22
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-matthew-21-22.py

Key decisions in this range:
- Triumphal Entry (21:1-11): classified as direct fulfillment — Zech 9:9 cited
  explicitly; "Son of David" from the crowd; royal entry without military might
- Temple Cleansing (21:12-17): classified as direct revelation — Jesus' authority claim
  over "my Father's house"; "my house" language identifies him as the Son
- Fig Tree (21:18-22): type — Israel's barren profession; also revelation of God
  showing the faith that moves mountains
- Authority Controversy (21:23-27): direct revelation — the authority of John and
  Jesus are from the same divine source; Jesus refuses to play the Sanhedrin's game
- Wicked Tenants (21:33-46): direct revelation/allegory — the son sent last is Jesus;
  v42 cornerstone already present; v43-44 missing
- Wedding Banquet (22:1-14): revelation of God — the king's son as the explicit figure
  for Jesus; the twice-refused invitation = Israel's rejection of the gospel
- Caesar question (22:15-22): revelation of God — "give to God what is God's" puts
  all human political claims under the divine claim
- Resurrection controversy (22:23-33): direct revelation — "God of Abraham... is God
  not of the dead but of the living"; Jesus corrects Sadducean theology authoritatively
- Greatest Commandment (22:34-40): direct revelation — Jesus identifies the two as
  the interpretive foundation of all Torah and the prophets
- David's Son (22:41-46): direct revelation — Jesus uses Ps 110:1 to claim he is more
  than David's descendant; v44 already present; v45-46 missing
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "21": {
    "1": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "Now when they drew near to Jerusalem and came to Bethphage, to the Mount of Olives, then Jesus sent two disciples." The approach to Jerusalem via Bethphage on the Mount of Olives is the specific geographical choreography of the royal entry. The Mount of Olives is the site where Zech 14:4 places YHWH\'s feet at the eschatological day of the LORD. Jesus descends from the exact site that the prophet associated with divine arrival. The Christological geography: the route is not incidental but prophetically loaded.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "Saying to them, \'Go into the village in front of you, and immediately you will find a donkey tied, and a colt with her. Untie them and bring them to me.\'" The prior knowledge of the tied donkey and colt — either by divine foreknowledge or pre-arrangement — demonstrates Jesus\' sovereign orchestration of his own prophetic fulfillment. The Christological precision: the details of the entry are under his control, not incidental. He enters Jerusalem as the one who scripts his own fulfillment of prophecy.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "If anyone says anything to you, you shall say, \'The Lord needs them,\' and he will send them at once." The "the Lord needs them" (<em>ho kyrios autōn chreian echei</em>) is both practical instruction and Christological self-identification. The Lord, who owns everything (Ps 24:1), declares need — the incarnate Son who has genuinely entered the condition of human dependency. The submission of the donkey\'s owner to this request is the submission of creation to its rightful Lord.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "This took place to fulfill what was spoken by the prophet, saying..." Matthew\'s fulfillment formula marks the entry as the conscious realization of prophetic Scripture. The Christological hermeneutic: the entry into Jerusalem is not a royal display that happens to resemble Zechariah; it is the deliberate enactment of the prophetic script. Jesus enters Jerusalem as the one who knows he is fulfilling the word of God.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "\'Say to the daughter of Zion, \'Behold, your king is coming to you, humble, and mounted on a donkey, on a colt, the foal of a beast of burden.\'\'" The citation of Zech 9:9 (combined with Isa 62:11) specifies the kind of kingship on display: not the war-horse of military conquest but the donkey of humble peace. The Christological kingship is a deliberate anti-type of Davidic warrior-kingship. The one who comes is the king of peace whose dominion will extend to the ends of the earth (Zech 9:10) — but by way of the cross, not the sword.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "The disciples went and did as Jesus had directed them." The disciples\' obedience to the precise instructions is the Christological partnership: they execute the prophetic script that Jesus directs. The entry into Jerusalem is not a spontaneous popular event but a carefully choreographed fulfillment of Scripture, with Jesus as both the subject of the prophecy and the director of its enactment.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "They brought the donkey and the colt and put on them their cloaks, and he sat on them." The spreading of cloaks on the animals is the disciples\' act of honor — preparing a royal seat for the king. The Christological symbolism: the humble king rides on borrowed animals, seated on disciples\' cloaks, entering the city where he will be crucified within the week. The royalty and the humility are inseparable.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "Most of the crowd spread their cloaks on the road, and others cut branches from the trees and spread them on the road." The spreading of cloaks on the road echoes 2 Kgs 9:13, where garments were spread before Jehu when he was proclaimed king. The palm branches echo the Feast of Tabernacles (Lev 23:40) and the Maccabean victory celebration (1 Macc 13:51). The crowd is acting out a coronation — the Christological import: they recognize something kingly, though they will misunderstand what kind of king has arrived.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "And the crowds that went before him and that followed him were shouting, \'Hosanna to the Son of David! Blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord! Hosanna in the highest!\'" The Hosanna-shout is a citation of Ps 118:25-26 (<em>hōshi\'a nā</em>, "save us, we pray"). The Christological identification: "Son of David" from the crowd affirms the messianic lineage; "he who comes in the name of the LORD" is the one sent from God. The Hosanna is both an exclamation of praise and a petition for salvation — "save us!" directed to the one who will do exactly that, though not in the way the crowd expects.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "And when he entered Jerusalem, the whole city was stirred up, saying, \'Who is this?\'" The stirring of the whole city (<em>eseisthē pasa hē polis</em> — the same verb for earthquake, <em>seismos</em>) is the Christological disruption that Jesus\' arrival always creates. The question "who is this?" echoes 12:23 ("Can this be the Son of David?") and is the question every person must answer. The whole city shaken by his arrival anticipates the earthquake at the resurrection (28:2) — the same presence that disrupts the earth.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "And the crowds said, \'This is the prophet Jesus, from Nazareth of Galilee.\'" The crowd\'s identification — "the prophet Jesus, from Nazareth of Galilee" — is the prophetic category, not the full messianic confession. They see more than an ordinary teacher but less than the Son of God. The Christological inadequacy of the crowd\'s answer echoes 16:14 (the popular identifications before Caesarea Philippi). Jesus is more than a prophet; the crowd\'s answer is the same category-error repeated at the triumphal entry.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct revelation: "And Jesus entered the temple and drove out all who sold and bought in the temple, and he overturned the tables of the money-changers and the seats of those who sold pigeons." The Temple Cleansing is the Christological authority-act that makes the messianic claim most explicit. Jesus enters the Temple — his Father\'s house (21:13) — and acts with the authority of its owner. The driving out is the act of the one who has standing to judge the Temple\'s use. Only the Son could do what the Son does here.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "He said to them, \'It is written, My house shall be called a house of prayer, but you make it a den of robbers.\'" The "my house" (<em>ho oikos mou</em>) is the Christological self-identification as the Son: the Temple belongs to his Father, and he speaks of it with filial ownership. The citation of Isa 56:7 (house of prayer for all peoples) paired with Jer 7:11 (den of robbers) is the prophetic indictment applied to the present situation. Jesus does not merely quote the prophets; he fulfills the prophetic office of calling Israel to account.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "And the blind and the lame came to him in the temple, and he healed them." The healing of the blind and lame in the Temple — immediately after the cleansing — is the Christological replacement of the commercial with the compassionate. The Temple becomes what it should be: the place of divine encounter and healing, not commercial transaction. Note: 2 Sam 5:8 associates the blind and lame with exclusion from the Temple; Jesus receives and heals the very ones previously excluded.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "But when the chief priests and the scribes saw the wonderful things that he did, and the children crying out in the temple, \'Hosanna to the Son of David!\' they were indignant." The chief priests\' indignation at the children\'s Hosanna is the Christological contrast: the religious establishment is outraged by the messianic worship that children offer freely. The children in the Temple crying "Son of David" complete the triumphal entry scene — the kingdom belongs to children (19:14), and the children recognize the king.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "And they said to him, \'Do you hear what these are saying?\' And Jesus said to them, \'Yes; have you never read, \'Out of the mouth of infants and nursing babies you have prepared praise?\'\'" The citation of Ps 8:2 — where the praise of infants silences the enemy — is the Christological counter to the chief priests\' objection. The children\'s worship is not an embarrassment but a fulfillment of Scripture: God has prepared praise from the mouths of the very young. The one who receives the children\'s worship is the one to whom the Psalm applies.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "And leaving them, he went out of the city to Bethany and lodged there." The withdrawal to Bethany — the village of Mary, Martha, and Lazarus — is the Christological pattern of withdrawal after confrontation: the Temple episode and its aftermath require a strategic retreat. The lodging in Bethany (2 miles from Jerusalem) is also the base for the final week\'s daily journey to and from Jerusalem. The one who has no permanent home (8:20) is hosted by friends on the way to his death.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A type: "In the morning, as he was returning to the city, he became hungry." The hunger of Jesus on the way back to Jerusalem is the genuine human vulnerability of the incarnate Son. The Christological resonance: the one who fed five thousand is himself hungry. The bodily need that will be the occasion for the fig tree\'s cursing is not staged but real. The Son of God who made himself nothing (Phil 2:7) experiences ordinary human hunger as he walks toward the passion.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A type: "And seeing a fig tree by the wayside, he went to it and found nothing on it but only leaves. And he said to it, \'May no fruit ever come from you again!\' And the fig tree withered at once." The cursing of the fig tree is the enacted parable of Israel\'s religious profession without fruit — leaves (external observance) without figs (genuine righteousness). The fig tree that promises fruit but produces none is the image of temple religion that has been cleansed (v.12-13) but will not produce the fruit of repentance (3:10). The immediate withering is the Christological judgment pronounced with divine authority.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "When the disciples saw it, they marveled, saying, \'How did the fig tree wither at once?\'" The disciples\' astonishment at the immediate withering focuses on the mechanism — "how?" — before Jesus redirects to the principle: faith in God. The Christological bearing: the miracle of the withered fig tree is not merely a display of power but a lesson in the relationship between faith and the authority the disciples have been given. The withering is the visible sign of the invisible verdict.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct revelation: "And Jesus answered them, \'Truly, I say to you, if you have faith and do not doubt, you will not only do what has been done to the fig tree, but even if you say to this mountain, \'Be taken up and thrown into the sea,\' it will happen.\'" The mountain-moving faith (already promised in 17:20) is the Christological extension of the fig-tree miracle: the disciples who receive Christ\'s faith can act with his authority. The mountain cast into the sea is the eschatological imagery of Zech 14:4 — the Mount of Olives split at the day of the LORD. Kingdom authority can accomplish what seems geologically impossible.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "And whatever you ask in prayer, you will receive, if you have faith." The prayer-promise connected to the fig-tree episode grounds answered prayer in faith. The Christological basis: the disciples pray in Jesus\' name (cf. John 14:13-14) — the authority of the name is the ground of confidence. Faith that asks is faith directed to the one who has all authority, and that authority is not withheld from those who ask in dependence on him.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct revelation: "And when he entered the temple, the chief priests and the elders of the people came up to him as he was teaching, and said, \'By what authority are you doing these things, and who gave you this authority?\'" The authority question — "by what authority?" — is the central Christological question of the passion week. The chief priests and elders challenge the basis of the Temple cleansing and the teaching. The Christological irony: the one who has all authority (28:18) is being interrogated about the source of his authority by the institution that should have recognized him.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct revelation: "Jesus answered them, \'I also will ask you one question, and if you tell me the answer, then I also will tell you by what authority I do these things.\'" The counter-question is the Christological epistemological move: to answer the authority-question directly would require them to either accept or explicitly reject his divine authority. The counter-question about John\'s baptism creates a dilemma that exposes their real position.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct revelation: "The baptism of John, from where did it come? From heaven or from man?\' And they discussed it among themselves, saying, \'If we say, From heaven, he will say to us, Why then did you not believe him?\'" The dilemma Jesus creates is the Christological trap: John\'s authority and Jesus\' authority are from the same source — and rejecting one requires rejecting the other. The chief priests\' calculation reveals they are not interested in truth but in political safety. The one who poses the dilemma knows their hearts.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "But if we say, From man, we are afraid of the crowd, for they all hold that John was a prophet." The fear of the crowd reveals that the chief priests\' rejection of John and Jesus is political rather than theological. The Christological exposure: those who should be theological authorities operate by crowd-management, not prophetic discernment. The authority they exercise is human not divine — the very charge they are bringing against Jesus turns back on them.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: "So they answered Jesus, \'We do not know.\' And he said to them, \'Neither will I tell you by what authority I do these things.\'" The refusal to answer ("we do not know") forfeits their claim to judge Jesus\' authority. The Christological verdict: those who will not acknowledge the Father\'s authority through John are unqualified to judge the Father\'s authority through the Son. The non-answer to the counter-question is itself an answer to the original question — by the authority the rejectors cannot name.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: "What do you think? A man had two sons. And he went to the first and said, \'Son, go and work in the vineyard today.\'" The Two Sons parable opens with a father-and-sons scenario that mirrors the Father-Son relationship throughout Matthew. The Christological setting: Jesus is speaking to the chief priests and elders who have just refused to answer his question. The parable will identify them with the son who says yes but does nothing.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: "And he answered, \'I will not,\' but afterward he changed his mind and went." The first son\'s refusal followed by repentance and obedience is the Christological portrait of the tax collectors and sinners who initially refused the kingdom\'s call but responded to John\'s preaching (v.32). The change of mind (<em>metamelomai</em>) is not the full metanoia of repentance but the practical turn to obedience. Action counts more than initial profession.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: "And he went to the other and said the same. And he answered, \'I go, sir,\' but did not go." The second son\'s profession without action is the Christological portrait of the chief priests who say "I go, Lord" with their mouths while their hearts and actions remain far from the Father. The religious establishment that professes to do the Father\'s will has not entered the kingdom. Verbal compliance without action is the anti-type of true discipleship.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A direct revelation: "Which of the two did the will of his father?\' They said, \'The first.\' Jesus said to them, \'Truly, I say to you, the tax collectors and the prostitutes go into the kingdom of God before you.\'" The verdict — tax collectors and prostitutes enter the kingdom before the chief priests — is the Christological inversion of religious expectation. The religiously despised (those who initially said "I will not") have entered through repentance; the religiously respectable (those who said "I go" but did not) have not. Kingdom entry is by changed life, not by position.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A direct revelation: "For John came to you in the way of righteousness, and you did not believe him, but the tax collectors and the prostitutes believed him. And even when you saw it, you did not afterward change your minds and believe him." The Christological indictment: the chief priests saw the effect of John\'s preaching on tax collectors and prostitutes — the first sons going to work in the vineyard — but did not change. The evidence of genuine repentance was visible to them and still did not move them. Hardness of heart is willful, not ignorant.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A direct revelation: "Hear another parable. There was a master of a house who planted a vineyard and put a fence around it and dug a winepress in it and built a tower and leased it to tenants, and went into a far country." The Wicked Tenants parable is an allegory drawn directly from Isa 5:1-7 (the Song of the Vineyard, where the vineyard is Israel). The householder who plants, fences, digs, builds, and leases is the Father who prepared Israel for the kingdom\'s harvest. The Christological setup: the master goes away, and the tenants\'  management of the vineyard will reveal their character.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "When the season for fruit drew near, he sent his servants to the tenants to get his fruit." The servants sent to collect the harvest are the prophets sent to Israel to call for the fruit of repentance and righteousness. The Christological frame: the entire prophetic tradition — from Moses to John — is the master\'s repeated sending of servants to collect what the vineyard owes.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: "And the tenants took his servants and beat one, killed another, and stoned another." The violence against the servants is the history of Israel\'s rejection of the prophets: beaten (Jeremiah in the stocks, Jer 20:2), killed (Uriah, Jer 26:23), stoned (Zechariah, 2 Chr 24:21). The Christological catalog: the servants\' fate is the fate of every prophet sent to call Israel to account. The pattern of rejection is not new — it is the recurring tragedy of the vineyard.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A revelation of God: "Again he sent other servants, more than the first. And they did the same to them." The repeated sending — more servants, the same rejection — is the divine patience with Israel across the centuries. The Christological bearing: the master does not give up after the first rejection. The multiplication of servants (prophets) before sending the son is the measure of the master\'s longsuffering. The final servant is not the first response but the culmination of a long history of attempts.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A direct revelation: "Finally he sent his son to them, saying, \'They will respect my son.\'" The sending of the son after all the servants have been rejected is the Christological identification of the parable\'s central point: Jesus is the Son sent last, after all the prophets. The master\'s expectation — "they will respect my son" — is the divine logic of incarnation: the Son, as the final and definitive word (Heb 1:1-2), will be recognized as the one the servants could not be. The expectation is tragically wrong — not the Father\'s miscalculation but the measure of the tenants\' wickedness.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A direct revelation: "But when the tenants saw the son, they said to themselves, \'This is the heir. Come, let us kill him and have his inheritance.\'" The recognition of the son — "this is the heir" — and the deliberate decision to kill him is the Christological indictment of the chief priests and Sanhedrin: they know who he is (or suspect it), and they choose murder over submission. The plan to seize the inheritance by killing the heir is the logic of those who want the kingdom without the king.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A direct revelation: "And they took him and threw him out of the vineyard and killed him." The killing of the son — thrown out of the vineyard before being killed — has the Christological detail that mirrors the passion: Jesus is led outside the city to be crucified (27:32; cf. Heb 13:12: "Jesus suffered outside the gate"). The parable predicts the spatial pattern of the passion: expelled from the city, then killed. The allegory is precise in its prophecy.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A direct revelation: "When therefore the owner of the vineyard comes, what will he do to those tenants?" The question Jesus poses to the chief priests will produce their own judgment on themselves. The Christological irony: the chief priests are about to pronounce their own eschatological sentence.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A direct revelation: "They said to him, \'He will put those wretches to a miserable death and let out the vineyard to other tenants who will give him the fruits in their seasons.\'" The chief priests\' own verdict — the wretches destroyed, the vineyard given to new tenants — is the Christological self-judgment. Without knowing it, they have announced the eschatological consequence of rejecting the Son: the vineyard will be taken and given to others (v.43). The judgment they pronounce is accurate and will be applied to them.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A direct revelation: "Therefore I tell you, the kingdom of God will be taken away from you and given to a people producing its fruits." The direct application of the parable to the chief priests is the Christological verdict: the vineyard (the kingdom of God) will be given to a people who produce fruit — the community of Jew and Gentile gathered around the crucified and risen Son. The Christological transfer: the nation-as-exclusive-vessel of the kingdom is superseded by the community constituted by faith in the Son.</p>',
    "44": '<p>A direct revelation: "And the one who falls on this stone will be broken to pieces; and when it falls on anyone, it will crush him." The stone of stumbling — Jesus as the cornerstone — causes two different forms of judgment: those who fall on it are broken; those on whom it falls are crushed. The Christological severity: rejection of the cornerstone is not merely religious failure but eschatological catastrophe. The same stone that is the foundation of the new temple (v.42) is the stone of judgment for those who refuse it (Isa 8:14-15; Dan 2:34-35, 44).</p>',
    "45": '<p>A revelation of God: "When the chief priests and the Pharisees heard his parables, they perceived that he was speaking about them." The recognition of self-incrimination — "he was speaking about them" — is the Christological moment of dawning clarity. The parables have been transparent enough that those with ears have heard. The chief priests and Pharisees now know exactly what Jesus thinks of their position, and they will respond not with repentance but with plotting.</p>',
    "46": '<p>A revelation of God: "And although they were seeking to arrest him, they feared the crowds, because they held him to be a prophet." The same political calculation as in 21:26 (fearing the crowd about John) now applies to Jesus. The Christological protection: the popular recognition of Jesus as a prophet prevents the arrest the Sanhedrin wants. The crowd\'s limited identification (prophet, not Messiah) is still sufficient to protect him — temporarily. The chief priests will find their opening in Judas (26:14-16), who avoids the crowds by enabling a nighttime arrest.'
  },
  "22": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: "And again Jesus spoke to them in parables, saying..." The continued parabolic address to the chief priests and Pharisees links the Wedding Banquet parable to the Wicked Tenants. The Christological frame: Jesus keeps teaching the religious authorities through parables — giving them opportunity to hear, while the form itself reveals their inability to receive.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct revelation: "The kingdom of heaven may be compared to a king who gave a wedding feast for his son." The Wedding Banquet parable is the most explicit allegory in the parables: the king is the Father, the son is the Son (Jesus), and the wedding feast is the eschatological celebration of the kingdom. The Christological identification: the entire history of salvation is the Father\'s preparation of the wedding feast to honor his Son. Rejecting the invitation is rejecting the Son whom the feast honors.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "And sent his servants to call those who were invited to the wedding feast, but they were not willing to come." The first sending — to those already invited (Israel, particularly the religious leadership) — is refused. "Not willing to come" (<em>ouk ēthelon elthein</em>) is the volitional refusal: not inability but unwillingness. The Christological bearing: the kingdom\'s invitation to those with the most preparation and expectation is the first and most culpable refusal.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "Again he sent other servants, saying, \'Tell those who are invited, \'See, I have prepared my dinner, my oxen and my fat calves have been slaughtered, and everything is ready. Come to the wedding feast.\'\'" The repeated, urgent invitation — "everything is ready" — is the urgency of the gospel: the preparation is complete, the feast is set, only the guests\' presence is lacking. The Christological urgency: the Son has come, the sacrifice has been made (the oxen and fat calves anticipate the cross), and the invitation is extended again.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "But they paid no attention and went off, one to his farm, another to his business." The indifference to the royal invitation — turning to ordinary business rather than the wedding — is the Christological diagnosis of the thorn-soil: "cares of the world and deceitfulness of riches choke the word" (13:22). The farm and business are not evil; the Christological problem is their priority over the kingdom\'s invitation. Ordinary life becomes the refusal of eschatological grace.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "While the rest seized his servants, treated them shamefully, and killed them." The violence against the servants mirrors the Wicked Tenants parable: the progression from indifference (v.5) to active hostility. The Christological pattern: rejection of the kingdom invitation escalates from inattention to persecution. The servants killed are the prophets and the apostles who bore the invitation.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "The king was angry, and he sent his troops and destroyed those murderers and burned their city." The burning of the city by the king\'s troops is a transparent reference to Jerusalem\'s destruction in 70 AD — the eschatological consequence of rejecting the Son\'s invitation. The Christological judgment: the murder of the servants and the rejection of the Son\'s wedding feast bring the judgment that Jesus predicted throughout the discourse (23:37-38; 24:1-2).</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then he said to his servants, \'The wedding feast is ready, but those who were invited were not worthy.\'" The unworthiness of the first-invited guests is not a fixed characteristic but the verdict on their refusal. The Christological inversion: those who seemed most worthy (the religious leaders, those long-prepared) proved unworthy by their refusal; the unworthy (Gentiles, sinners, outsiders) will be made worthy by accepting the invitation.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "Go therefore to the main roads and invite to the wedding feast as many as you find." The going to the main roads — the broad roads where all kinds of people travel — is the Christological Great Commission in parabolic form. The invitation goes to everyone regardless of preparation or qualification. The "therefore" connects the new mission to the rejection of the first: because the first-invited refused, the whole world becomes the field of invitation.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "And those servants went out into the roads and gathered all whom they found, both bad and good. So the wedding hall was filled with guests." The mixed assembly — bad and good — is the Christological reality of the present kingdom: both wheat and weeds (13:24-30), both good fish and bad (13:47-50). The full wedding hall represents the church\'s present mixed condition. The final separation (vv.11-13) is the eschatological judgment that distinguishes genuine from false response.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "But when the king came in to look at the guests, he saw there a man who had no wedding garment." The man without a wedding garment represents those who enter the community of the called without the garment of genuine righteousness — the "putting on Christ" (Rom 13:14) that constitutes genuine response. The Christological bearing: entry into the feast-community is necessary but not sufficient; the garment of new life is required. The wedding garment is not earned but given — refusing it is the second form of refusal.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "And he said to him, \'Friend, how did you get in here without a wedding garment?\' And he was speechless." The "Friend" (<em>hetaire</em>) is the same address as the workers (20:13) and Judas (26:50) — the address to those who are in proximity but not in genuine relationship. The speechlessness before the king is the Christological image of the judgment day when no defense is possible (cf. Rom 3:19: "every mouth may be stopped"). The one without the garment has nothing to say.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then the king said to the attendants, \'Bind him hand and foot and cast him into the outer darkness. In that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.\'" The outer darkness and weeping — the seventh occurrence of this formula in Matthew (8:12; 13:42, 50; 22:13; 24:51; 25:30) — is the Christological refrain of eschatological exclusion. Those who refuse the invitation and those who enter without the garment share the same end: exclusion from the feast. The kingdom\'s joy and the judgment\'s darkness are the two destinations.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct revelation: "For many are called, but few are chosen." The closing maxim of the Wedding Banquet parable is the Christological summary of election and response: the call goes to all ("many"), but the chosen are those who receive it genuinely. The Christological tension: the invitation is universal (go to all the roads), but not all who hear it receive it with the genuine response that the garment represents. Election is not hostility to the un-chosen but the fulfillment of the grace genuinely received.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then the Pharisees went and plotted how to entangle him in his talk." The conspiracy to trap Jesus in his speech is the Christological confrontation with hostile testing. The three tests that follow (Caesar, resurrection, greatest commandment) are political, theological, and legal traps designed to make Jesus choose a position that alienates some constituency. The one who speaks only truth answers each trap without being caught.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "And they sent their disciples to him, along with the Herodians, saying, \'Teacher, we know that you are true and teach the way of God truthfully, and you do not care about anyone\'s opinion, for you are not swayed by appearances.\'" The flattery before the trap is the Christological test of vanity: will Jesus be moved by praise? The affirmations they make — true, teaches God\'s way, not swayed by appearances — are all accurate descriptions of the Son of God. The trap is set inside a genuine description of who he is.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "Tell us, then, what you think. Is it lawful to pay taxes to Caesar, or not?" The Caesar-question is a political dilemma: say yes, alienate the nationalists; say no, invite Roman charges of sedition. The Christological response will transcend the binary by reframing the question at a higher level — not which human authority to obey but what belongs to whom.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "But Jesus, aware of their malice, said, \'Why put me to the test, you hypocrites?\'" The awareness of their malice — divine perception of hidden motive — is the Christological knowledge of the human heart (cf. 9:4; 12:25). The naming of the test as malice is the prophetic unmasking: behind the flattery is hostility. The "hypocrites" charge names the gap between the flattering words and the malicious intent.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "Show me the coin for the tax.\' And they brought him a denarius." The coin produced belongs to the tribute money — a Roman denarius bearing the emperor\'s image and inscription. The Christological economy: Jesus does not refuse the coin or its use; he uses it to draw the distinction between imperial and divine claims.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "And Jesus said to them, \'Whose likeness and inscription is this?\' They said, \'Caesar\'s.\'" The image and inscription on the coin are the tokens of Caesar\'s ownership-claim. The Christological counterpart: human beings bear the image of God (<em>eikōn tou theou</em>, Gen 1:26-27) — the inscription of God\'s ownership. The coin with Caesar\'s image belongs to Caesar; the person with God\'s image belongs to God.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct revelation: "He said to them, \'Therefore render to Caesar the things that are Caesar\'s, and to God the things that are God\'s.\' When they heard it, they marveled and left him and went away." The "render to God what is God\'s" is the Christological trump card: everything ultimately belongs to God, including Caesar himself. The astonishment of the questioners is the recognition that they have been out-argued at the deepest level — the question about taxes has become a question about the image of God in every human being. The trap failed.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "When they heard it, they marveled and left him and went away." The departure of the Pharisees and Herodians — without a further word — is the Christological victory in the controversy. They came with a trap; they leave with the trap unanswered in their hands. The one who answers unanswerable questions has authority they cannot match.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct revelation: "The same day Sadducees came to him, who say that there is no resurrection, and they asked him a question." The Sadducees — who accepted only the Pentateuch and denied resurrection — present the resurrection-dilemma. The Christological context: Jesus is himself the resurrection (John 11:25) and is about to demonstrate it. The one being questioned about resurrection will be raised from the dead within the week. The question is asked in the presence of its answer.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "Saying, \'Teacher, Moses said, If a man dies having no children, his brother must marry the widow and raise up offspring for his brother.\'" The levirate marriage law (Deut 25:5-6) is the Sadducean setup for the absurd scenario of v.25-28. The Christological bearing: they use Mosaic law to argue against resurrection, but Jesus will use Mosaic law to argue for it (v.31-32: Exod 3:6). The same Torah contains both the levirate law and the resurrection-implication; Jesus reads it with more depth than those who reject the resurrection.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: "Now there were seven brothers among us. The first married and died, and having no offspring left his wife to his brother." The hypothetical chain of seven levirate marriages — designed to make resurrection seem absurd — is the Sadducean thought experiment. The Christological response will not engage the hypothetical directly but will expose the faulty premise: resurrection life is not the continuation of earthly categories.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "So too the second and third, down to the seventh." The escalation to seven (the number of completeness) makes the hypothetical maximally absurd. The Christological response will show that the absurdity is created by assuming resurrection = resuscitation. The new creation body is not constrained by the institutions of the old creation.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "After them all, the woman died." The woman\'s death after all seven husbands completes the hypothetical. The Sadducean question assumes the woman\'s resurrection entails a legal conflict: which husband? The Christological answer will dissolve the conflict by dissolving the premise.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: "In the resurrection, therefore, of the seven, whose wife will she be? For they all had her." The "therefore" of the Sadducean question is their logical conclusion: resurrection creates an insoluble legal problem. The Christological reply will expose that the "therefore" rests on a misunderstanding of what resurrection is.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct revelation: "But Jesus answered them, \'You are wrong, because you know neither the Scriptures nor the power of God.\'" The double charge — wrong about Scripture and wrong about divine power — is the Christological authority of the one who knows both. The Sadducees\' error is not merely hermeneutical but theological: they have limited God\'s power to what they know from earthly experience. The one who will rise from the dead tells them their limits.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A direct revelation: "For in the resurrection they neither marry nor are given in marriage, but are like angels in heaven." The resurrection state is not the extension of earthly institutions but a new mode of existence. The Christological bearing: the one who will be the first to be raised (1 Cor 15:20) announces the shape of resurrection life. Marriage belongs to the old creation order (Gen 2:18-25); the new creation involves a different mode of communal existence. The Sadducean hypothetical dissolves because its premise (resurrection = earthly life continued) is false.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A direct revelation: "And as for the resurrection of the dead, have you not read what was said to you by God..." The "said to you by God" (<em>to rhēthen hymin hypo tou theou</em>) is the Christological reading of Scripture: these words in Exodus are not merely historical record but divine address to every hearer in every generation. The same God who spoke to Moses speaks through the text to those who read it. The living Scripture addresses the living community.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A direct revelation: "\'I am the God of Abraham, and the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob\'? He is not God of the dead, but of the living." The Christological argument from Exod 3:6 is logical and theological: God says "I am" (present tense) the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob — who had been dead for centuries when Moses heard this. If God is their God in the present tense, they must be alive. God is in a living relationship with them; therefore they live. The one who makes this argument will himself be alive after death to confirm it.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: "And when the crowd heard it, they were astonished at his teaching." The crowd\'s astonishment at the resurrection-argument is the Christological effect of teaching with authority. The Sadducees\' challenge has been turned into an argument for resurrection from within the Pentateuch they accepted. The one who teaches like this teaches not as a scribe but as the one who gave the Scriptures and knows their deepest intent.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "But when the Pharisees heard that he had silenced the Sadducees, they gathered together." The Pharisees\' regrouping after the Sadducees\' failure is the Christological relay of opposition: each group takes a turn testing Jesus and failing. The gathering of the Pharisees after the Sadducees\' defeat is the sustained opposition that will end only at the cross.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: "And one of them, a lawyer, asked him a question to test him." The lawyer\'s question — "to test him" (<em>peirazōn</em>, the temptation-word) — is the third Christological test of the Jerusalem week, following the Caesar-question and the resurrection-question. The testing continues; the one being tested is the same one who passed the wilderness test and every subsequent test.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A revelation of God: "Teacher, which is the great commandment in the Law?" The greatest-commandment question was a live rabbinic debate. The Christological significance: Jesus will give an answer that is not merely the best of the competing options but the interpretive key to the entire Torah. His answer does not choose between candidates but identifies the structure that holds all commandments together.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A direct revelation: "And he said to him, \'You shall love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind.\'" The citation of Deut 6:5 (the Shema\'s love-command) as the first and great commandment is the Christological affirmation of Israel\'s central confession. The one who cites "love the Lord your God" is himself the object of that love — the one in whom "the Lord your God" has become present. Loving God with all one\'s heart, soul, and mind is, in Matthew\'s Christology, loving the Son through whom the Father is made known.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A direct revelation: "This is the great and first commandment." The identification of the love-commandment as "great and first" (<em>megalē kai prōtē</em>) establishes it as the foundation from which all other commandments are derived and interpreted. The Christological bearing: the entire moral teaching of Jesus throughout the Gospel (the Sermon on the Mount, the community discourse, the conflict stories) is the explication of this first commandment — love for God that takes form in concrete human relationships.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A direct revelation: "And a second is like it: You shall love your neighbor as yourself." The citation of Lev 19:18 as the second commandment "like" the first establishes the inseparability of love for God and love for neighbor. The Christological integration: the one who embodies both — who loves the Father perfectly and gives himself for his neighbors completely — is the one who cites both as the summary of Torah. The two-commandment summary is the description of Jesus\' own life.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A direct revelation: "On these two commandments depend all the Law and the Prophets." The hanging of "all the Law and the Prophets" on the two love-commandments is the Christological hermeneutic that has governed Jesus\' teaching throughout Matthew. The Law and the Prophets (5:17: "I have come not to abolish them but to fulfill them") are fulfilled by the one who loves God perfectly and loves his neighbor to death. The cross is the supreme act of the double love-commandment.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A direct revelation: "Now while the Pharisees were gathered together, Jesus asked them a question." The Christological reversal: after three tests in which the Pharisees tested Jesus, Jesus now asks the definitive question. The questioner becomes the questioned. The one who has answered every test now poses the test that cannot be answered from within their framework.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A direct revelation: "Saying, \'What do you think about the Christ? Whose son is he?\' They said to him, \'The son of David.\'" The Pharisees\' answer — "Son of David" — is correct as far as it goes (the Davidic descent of the Messiah is the standard expectation). The Christological trap: "Son of David" is true but insufficient. The Messiah is more than David\'s descendant; he is David\'s Lord. The question will expose the inadequacy of their messianic categories.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A direct revelation: "He said to them, \'How is it then that David, in the Spirit, calls him Lord, saying...\'" The "in the Spirit" (<em>en pneumati</em>) identifies the source of Ps 110\'s authority: David did not write from political imagination but under divine inspiration. The Christological hermeneutic: Scripture is Spirit-inspired, which means its meaning exceeds what the human author consciously intended. David in the Spirit wrote about the Messiah he could not fully see — and Jesus, who is the Messiah, can read what David\'s Spirit-given words point toward.</p>',
    "45": '<p>A direct revelation: "If then David calls him Lord, how is he his son?" The logical question — if David (the ancestor) calls the Messiah "Lord" (the superior), how can the Messiah be merely David\'s descendant? — is the Christological demonstration of the inadequacy of the "Son of David" category alone. The Messiah must be more than human descent can explain. He must be, as the Nicene Creed will say, "God from God" — the divine Son who entered David\'s line, not merely the human product of that line.</p>',
    "46": '<p>A direct revelation: "And no one was able to answer him a word, nor from that day did anyone dare to ask him any more questions." The silencing of all questioners — Pharisees, Herodians, Sadducees, lawyers — is the Christological authority-demonstration of the Jerusalem controversy. He has answered every test perfectly, exposed every trap, and posed one question that no one can answer. The silence before the Son of God is the prelude to the trial where they will finally succeed — not by answering him but by bribing Judas and manipulating Pilate.'
  }
}

